{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem *Sair-e-Falak* (\"A Celestial Journey\"), the speaker embarks on a visionary voyage across the heavens accompanied by Imagination.[^1] He flies onward through the cosmic blue, unobserved by any soul in the upper air, while the stars gaze in wonder at his secret journey.[^2] Transcending the boundaries of dusk, dawn, and the solar system, he beholds paradisiacal visions—including Iram, the birds singing on Tooba's bough, unveiled Houris, and graceful Saqis serving goblets—before perceiving a distant dark, frozen abode revealed by the angel Surosh to be Hell itself.[^3] The speaker inquires of Surosh about this grim place, learning that damned souls bring their own embers from earthly lives.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [ch. 18](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/#p-7bcfb8).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [ch. 18](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/#p-0f9fb1).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [ch. 18](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/).\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [ch. 18](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/#p-3ccdfb).",
